Differential Kinematics

Differential Kinematics is the study of robot motion using velocities.

Why study differential kinematics?

It allows us to study:

  • Non-Holonomic Robots, or robots whose pose is not uniquely defined by a single set of joint angles. The Romi and other mobile robots are non-holonomic because simply specifying their wheel angles does not tell you where they are in the world frame! The entire time history of a non-holonomic robot's motion is required to solve for its pose using integration of velocities.
  • Forces and torques in robot links and joints! This is because differential kinematics is a dual problem to the static analysis of forces and torques, given that the robot's links can be considered idealized power transducers.
  • velocities of a robot's links rather than positions. This can be useful if an inverse kinematic solution for a robot is not readily available, because it can allow us to drive a robot towards a goal location in task space.

Terminology for differential kinematics

In differential kinematics, we will be studying linear and angular velocities. If a robot end effector's velocity is given by:

\begin{equation} \vec{v}_p = \begin{bmatrix}v_x & v_y & v_z \end{bmatrix}^T \end{equation}

And its angular velocity is given by:

\begin{equation} \vec{\omega}_p = \begin{bmatrix}\omega_x & \omega_y & \omega_z \end{bmatrix}^T \end{equation}

We can define a "generalized velocity" for the robot in task space, called a twist, as:

\begin{equation} \vec{\mathcal{V}}_p = \begin{bmatrix}v_x & v_y & v_z & \omega_x & \omega_y & \omega_z \end{bmatrix}^T \end{equation}

Forward Differential Kinematics

The problem of forward differential kinematics, or the mapping from a twist in configuration space to a twist in task space, is summarized in Equation 4 below.

\begin{equation} \vec{\mathcal{V}}_p = J(\vec{q})\dot{\vec{q}} \end{equation}

\begin{equation} \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}v_x \\ v_y \\ v_z \\ \omega_x \\ \omega_y \\ \omega_z \end{bmatrix}}_{\vec{\mathcal{V}}} = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} \frac{\partial x}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial x}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial x}{\partial q_n} \\ \frac{\partial y}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial y}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial y}{\partial q_n} \\ \frac{\partial z}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial z}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial z}{\partial q_n} \\ \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial \phi}{\partial q_n} \\ \frac{\partial \theta}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial \theta}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial \theta}{\partial q_n} \\ \frac{\partial \psi}{\partial q_1} & \frac{\partial \psi}{\partial q_2} & \cdots & \frac{\partial \psi}{\partial q_n} \\ \end{bmatrix}}_{J(\vec{q})} \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} \dot{q}_1 \\ \dot{q}_2 \\ \vdots \\ \dot{q}_n \end{bmatrix}}_{\dot{\vec{q}}} \end{equation}

Example: Forward Differential Kinematics for a Two-Link Robot

Looking at our forward kinematic equations for the Artybot, we saw:

\begin{equation} ^Ax_P = l_2\cos\theta_2+ l_3\left(\cos\theta_2\cos\theta_3 - \sin\theta_2\sin\theta_3\right) \end{equation} \begin{equation} ^Ay_P = l_2\sin\theta_2 + l_3\left(\sin\theta_2\cos\theta_3 + \cos\theta_2\sin\theta_3\right) \end{equation}

ArtyBot forward differential kinematics

Computing the Jacobian matrix for forward differential kinematics requires taking the following partial derivatives:

\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \frac{\partial ^Ax_p}{\partial \theta_2} &= - l_2\sin\theta_2 + l_3\left(-\sin\theta_2\cos\theta_3 - \cos\theta_2\sin\theta_3\right) \\ \frac{\partial ^Ay_p}{\partial \theta_2} &= l_2\cos\theta_2 + l_3\left(\cos\theta_2\cos\theta_3 - \sin\theta_2\sin\theta_3\right) \\ \frac{\partial ^Ax_p}{\partial \theta_3} &= -l_3\left(\cos\theta_2\sin\theta_3 + \sin\theta_2\cos\theta_3\right) \\ \frac{\partial ^Ay_p}{\partial \theta_3} &= l_3\left(-\sin\theta_2\sin\theta_3 + \cos\theta_2\cos\theta_3\right) \end{aligned} \end{equation}

Then, the forward differential kinematic equation for the Artybot can be written:

\begin{equation} \begin{bmatrix} ^A\dot{x}_p \\ ^A\dot{y}_p \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{\partial ^Ax_p}{\partial \theta_2} & \frac{\partial ^Ax_p}{\partial \theta_3} \\ \frac{\partial ^Ay_p}{\partial \theta_2} & \frac{\partial ^Ay_p}{\partial \theta_3} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \dot{\theta}_2 \\ \dot{\theta_3}\end{bmatrix} \end{equation}

Example: Romi Forward Differential Kinematics

We have actually done differential kinematics for the Romi before when we studied Odometry!! As a reminder, The problem setup looked something like this:

Romi Forward Differential Kinematics

What we found was that:

\begin{equation} \dot{\psi} = \frac{v_R-v_L}{2r} \end{equation}

and

\begin{equation} v_b = \frac{v_L+v_R}{2} \end{equation}

Romi Forward Differential Kinematics

As it turns out, this already was a statement of forward differential kinematics (in body-fixed coordinates, rather than task space or allocentric coordinates). Noting that if the radius of the Romi's wheels is $R_w$, $v_R = \omega_R R_w$ and $v_L = \omega_L R_w$, and considering the Romi's configuration space as $\begin{bmatrix} \omega_R & \omega_L\end{bmatrix}^T$, we can write:

\begin{equation} \begin{bmatrix}^B\dot{x} \\ ^B\dot{y} \\ ^B\dot{\psi} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{R_w}{2} & \frac{R_w}{2} \\ 0 & 0 \\\frac{R_w}{2r} & -\frac{R_w}{2r} \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} \omega_R \\ \omega_L\end{bmatrix} \end{equation}

Romi Forward Differential Kinematics

The body-fixed velocity vector $^B\vec{v}$ can easily be transformed into allocentric coordinates using the rotation matrix $_B^AR(\psi) = \begin{bmatrix}\cos\psi& -\sin\psi \\ \sin\psi& \cos\psi \end{bmatrix}$, which alllows us to write the forward kinematic equation for task space directly:

\begin{equation} \begin{bmatrix}^A\dot{x} \\ ^A\dot{y} \\ ^A\dot{\psi} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{R_w\cos\psi}{2} & \frac{R_w\cos \psi}{2} \\ \frac{R_w\sin\psi}{2} & -\frac{R_w\sin \psi}{2}\\\frac{R_w}{2r} & -\frac{R_w}{2r} \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} \omega_R \\ \omega_L\end{bmatrix} \end{equation}

Note that in Equation 12, there is no explicit dependence of J on wheel angles $\theta_L,\theta_R$, but in Equation 13, there is dependence on $\psi$, which is not directly related to either $\theta_L$ or $\theta_R$. This is a statement of the robot's non-holonomic nature-- to know $\psi$, we need the entire time history of $\theta_L$ and $\theta_R$! We cannot simply map $\psi$ to those wheel angles directly, like we could with ArtyBot.

Inverse Differential Kinematics

If the robot's Jacobian is invertible, the inverse differential kinematic equation, which maps generalized velocities in task space to generalized joint velocities, is given by:

\begin{equation} \dot{\vec{q}} = J(\vec{q})^{-1}\vec{\mathcal{V}} \end{equation}

For J to be invertible, its determinant cannot be zero, and it must be square. Often, however, J is not square, because the dimensionality of the task and configuration spaces for the robot are not the same. In those cases, we can use the pseudoinverse of J:

\begin{equation} J^+ = J^T\left(JJ^T\right)^{-1} \end{equation}

Using inverse differential kinematics to reach a goal in task space

If the subscript "d" indicates a static "goal" value, and we define "eror" for the robot's end effector in task space as:

\begin{equation} \vec{e} = \begin{bmatrix} x_d-x & y_d - y& \cdots & \omega_{nd} - \omega_n \end{bmatrix}^T \end{equation}

Then we can progressively drive a robot's end effector towards the goal using the pseudoinverse of its Jacobian matrix:

\begin{equation} \dot{\vec{q}}= J^+ e \end{equation}

As error gets smaller, the robot will move more and more slowly and (hopefully) approach the goal.

Exercise: Make Romi move with a specified forward velocity and yaw rate.

If we wanted Romi to move in a circle of radius $R$ at some foward speed $U$, we could compute a goal yaw rate for the robot as:

\begin{equation} \psi_g = \frac{U}{R} \end{equation}

This means that we could specify a "goal" for the Romi's body-fixed task space as:

\begin{equation} \dot{\vec{q}_g} = \begin{bmatrix}^B\dot{x}_g & ^B\dot{y}_g & ^B\dot{\psi}_g\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}U & 0 & \frac{U}{R}\end{bmatrix} \end{equation}

Then, we could make the Romi achieve this goal in its "body-fixed task space" by moving its wheels at:

\begin{equation} \dot{\vec{q}} = \begin{bmatrix}\omega_R \\ \omega_L\end{bmatrix} = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} \frac{R_w}{2} & \frac{R_w}{2} \\ 0 & 0 \\\frac{R_w}{2r} & -\frac{R_w}{2r} \end{bmatrix}^+}_{J^+}\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}U \\ 0 \\ \frac{U}{R}\end{bmatrix}}_{\vec{\mathcal{V}}_b} \end{equation}

Exercise: Make Romi move with a specified forward velocity and yaw rate.

In the Week09_World in Webots, implement inverse differential kinematics as shown above to achieve any given yaw rate and any given forward speed. There is a "Starter Controller" in that world for your use. You will need to:

  • Calculate wheel speeds
  • compute yaw rate
  • compute forward Romi speed
  • Compute the Jacobian
  • Compute the pseudoinverse of the Jacobian
  • Compute wheel speeds needed to achieve the desired yaw rate and forward velocity, ultimately achieving your goal turn radius $R$.

Finally, use the supervisor to compare Romi's actual motion with your goal for its motion.
